<HEADLINE>
FT  14 MAY 91 / Bill to free travel fails to pass
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN LLOYD
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Soviet parliament last night again failed to guarantee its citizens the
right of free travel abroad, after one of the Supreme Soviet's two houses
refused to pass an emigration bill on grounds of expense, writes John Lloyd
in Moscow.
The bill has been two years in preparation, and received its first reading
18 months ago. It will probably come back to the Supreme Soviet on Thursday,
when a commission set up to break the impasse is expected to produce a
compromise.
Mr Vladimir Petrovsky, a deputy foreign minister, said yesterday that
discussion of the bill was confined to expense and technicalities, not to
principles. However, many of those arguing against the bill were from the
hardline Soyuz camp.
The bill guarantees that Soviet citizens who apply to travel abroad will
receive their passports within a month, while those who wish to emigrate
will get them in three months. . No Soviet citizen will be denied entry, as
many dissidents have in the past.
</TEXT>
