   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SIR LEON Brittan, the senior UK commissioner, yesterday urged the UK
government to drop its proposal for a 'hard Ecu' in favour of improving the
existing Ecu basket unit.
He did not link this with the overture by Mr Jacques Delors that Britain be
offered a let-out in the emu treaty.
The hard Ecu had proved 'politically valuable', Sir Leon said, showing that
the UK government was taking part in the Emu debate constructively. But, for
economic reasons, it had drawn little support from UK partners.
Sir Leon derided Britons who regarded the let-out on Emu as a trap or a form
of blackmail. There was no underhand deceit in the proposal, nor could be it
be considered blackmail for Britain's partners to try to make Emu such a
success that the UK would feel impelled to join.
